MotoGP - exploring the corelation between age and performance of the MotoGP rider.¶

1. Introduction¶

I struggled a little to find the right data set for my project. I wanted to do somthing orginal and unique. For my final project for Introduction to Programming II I chose to do Data Visualization, so I alredy anlalized some data about Climate change, Pay gap between Male/female etc. as well as Life expectancy in different countries. (link here)

As I'm a big fan of MotoGP I was curious if I can find something interesting regarding this topic. Fortunately, there is a dataset available on kaggle.com - MotoGP Race Results

Through this project, I dived into the details of the dataset. I will try to find interesting patterns and trends within the data. My main goal is to examine the performance of famous riders, understand how age affects race outcomes, and explore the "Did Not Finish" incidents during different seasons. This dataset has a lot of interesting values, like rider's number, race time or even average race speed. Let me take you on to journey through the world of the data of the King's class of motorbike racing.

For the purpose of this project I try to put myself in a position of a Junior Data Scientist at Dorna (the company that organizes MotoGP) that was assigned a task of finding valuable and interesting data from a provided raw dataset, without any clear objective. The goal is to explore the data based on my knowlege of the topic, draw some conclusions from my findings and the data provided and set objectives as I go through the exploratory phase.

1.1 About Dataset¶

This dataset contains comprehensive results of MotoGP races from various years, categories and circuits. It includes information such as the year of the race, the category of the race, the circuit name, the rider and team information, the bike used, the rider's position, the points earned and the country of the rider. The dataset also includes other additional information like the speed, number and time of the rider. This dataset is suitable for anyone looking to analyze the results of MotoGP races and gain insights into the performance of riders, teams and circuits. The dataset contains 56396 rows and 15 columns and is in a pandas Dataframe format

  • year: The year in which the race took place.
  • category: The category of the race such as MotoGP, Moto2, Moto3 etc.
  • sequence: The sequence of the race in the season.
  • shortname: A short name of the circuit where the race took place.
  • circuit_name: The name of the circuit where the race took place.
  • rider: A unique identifier for the rider.
  • rider_name: The name of the rider.
  • team_name: The name of the team the rider was riding for.
  • bike_name: The name of the bike used by the rider.
  • position: The final position of the rider in the race.
  • points: The number of points earned by the rider in the race.
  • number: The number worn by the rider during the race.
  • country: The country of the rider.
  • speed: The average speed of the rider during the race.
  • time: The time taken by the rider to complete the race

1.2 Ethical considerations¶

1.2.1 - Scraping the data¶

MotoGP official website does not allow for using the data provided on their website unless it's specifically said so.

After taking a closer look on the Terms of Use, I've found that unfortunately points 1 and 3 state respectively Any unauthorised use of the content of Dorna Channels will be prosecuted. Unless a specific Content is expressly authorised for downloading and it is so stated, the Content may not be downloaded. Consequently, any unauthorised download is a legal infringement with all its consequences. and You are only authorised to use Dorna Channels for personal purposes. You are therefore an end consumer and not a retailer or merchant. You are not permitted to provide, copy, exchange, modify, sell or transmit any Content that you access through the Dorna Channels for any purpose, whether for profit or free of charge..

For the most part I relied on the data available on Wikipedia. However, scraping the data from this popular source is very inacurate and requires a lot of cleaning.

1.2.2 Onward use / reuseage of data and derived data¶

The utilization of the source data, requires compliance with the terms and conditions stipulated by each publication during that period. Additionally, obtaining separate permission for usage may be necessary. It is important to note that any data derived from the source, would be subject to the same restrictions as the source text itself.

The analysis and conclusions presented in this project are entirely my own and independent of the original sources.

Checking the site I visited earlier, I see that birthday is stored under <span class="bday">1993-02-17</span>.

Since there is a special class dedicated to birthdays this should be a pretty easy task. I will store the birthdays in a dictionary where the rider's name is a key, and birthday is a value as it allows for quick access based on the name. If I need to use it in the future I can easily access it iterating over the names from the table.

Briefly looking through the file exported on the first iteration of the bthday_scraper() function, and checking some of the riders that I know, I see that for the majority of riders the birthdate is correct, however, I see that there is at least one incorrect value in the file, this is Jack Miller that was born on 18 January 1995, while the data scraped from the internet shows 1992-07-10.

While investigating the edge cases I found that there are more entries for the same name in Wikipedia. However, I noticed that in a link for a rider's page in Wikipedia where there is someone else with same name the string "_(motorcyclist)" is added at the end. I'll try to scrape the data again with the condition to first try to find the link with "(motorcyclist)" at the end.

Note: The code below is the final iteration, as it turned out that there were a lot of wrong values returned as there are more people with the same name and last name as some of the riders.

In [ ]:
## IMPORTANT NOTICE - This part scrapes the data from over 2500 separate Wikipedia pages. It took my computer almost 40 minutes to run.
## It's now commented out to avoid accidental running.


def bthday_scraper():
    
    birthday_dict2 = {}

    for name in formatted_names:
        url_with_motorcyclist = f"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/{name}_(motorcyclist)"
        response = requests.get(url_with_motorcyclist)
        soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')
        bday_element = soup.find('span', class_='bday')

        if bday_element:
            birthday = bday_element.text
        else:
            url = f"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/{name}"
            response = requests.get(url)
            soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')
            bday_element = soup.find('span', class_='bday')

            if bday_element:
                birthday = bday_element.text
            else:
                birthday_dict2[name] = np.nan

        birthday_dict2[name] = birthday
        birthday = np.nan

    birthday_dict2

I will save it as a .csv file. It might come in handy in a future exlporation.

    filename = './MotoGP race results/birthday_data2.csv'

    with open(filename, 'w', newline='') as file:
        writer = csv.writer(file)
        writer.writerow(['Name', 'Birthday'])

        for name, birthday in birthday_dict2.items():
            writer.writerow([name, birthday])

    print("CSV file exported successfully.")

In [ ]:
# Function to get the legends names from the web

def legends_list():
    url = "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MotoGP_Hall_of_Fame"
    table_class = "vcard"

    response = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, "html.parser")

    names = []
    rows = soup.find_all(class_=table_class)

    for row in rows[0:]:  # Skip the header row
        name_element = row.find("a")
        if name_element:
            name = name_element.get_text(strip=True)
            names.append(name.replace(" ", "_"))

    names

Again I'll export it to .csv file to use in the future.

    filename = './MotoGP race results/MotoGP_Hall_of_fame.csv'

    with open(filename, 'w', newline='') as file:
        writer = csv.writer(file)
        writer.writerow(['Name'])

        for name in names:
            writer.writerow([name])

    print("CSV file exported successfully.")

Part 3 - Hypothesis & Data anylysis¶

During the first part of this project I explored the data provided. While doing so, few questions crossed my mind. I'll try to analize the data that I now have and prove or disprove my working hypotheses.

  1. MotoGP Legends have high success rate at the begining of their career while for the most riders, success comes with their experience.

  2. The older the rider is the more likely it is that he will finish the race. (less DNF's - negative positions in a data set).

  3. There are more DNF's at the first half of the season, then at the second half of the season.

3.1 - MotoGP Legends have high success rate at the begining of their career while for the most riders, success comes with their experience.¶

3.1 Conclusion:¶

Legends much quicker get to their peak performance, while non-legends get to their peak performance around age 35. My hypothesis turned out to be true. The graph above clearly shows that non-legends improve their race scores up to the age of 36, while legends get to their peak performance on average at the age of 21 and keep it up to the age of 27 where it slowly starts degrading.

The values approaching 40 in the Age axis look like anomalies. This needs further investigation

3.2 - The older the rider is the more likely it is that he will finish the race. (less DNF's - negative positions in a data set).¶

For better visualization, I will represent my findings by the percentage of the finished races in predefined age groups.

In [ ]:
age_intervals = [15,17,20,22,25,27,30,32,35,37,40,42,45,47,50,53,55]

# new column for age groups in the DataFrame
df['age_group'] = pd.cut(df['age'], bins=age_intervals).astype(str)

# the percentage of riders finishing the race for each age group
finish_percentage = df[df['position'] > 0].groupby('age_group')['rider_name'].count() / df.groupby('age_group')['rider_name'].count() * 100


plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

plt.show()

3.2 Conclusion:¶

It's easy to see that young riders are less likely to finish the race than older riders. The steady increase in percentage is consistent with the experience gathered by the rider.

3.3 - There are more DNF's at the first half of the season, then at the second half of the season.¶

This is the most challenging to present as there is a lot of factors and calculations that need to be performed in order to acuratly represent this data.

In [ ]:
dnf_df = df[df['position'] < 0]

# group by year and sequence, count the number of DNFs in each group
dnf_counts = dnf_df.groupby(['year', 'sequence']).size().reset_index(name='dnf_count')

# number of races in each year
total_races = df.groupby('year')['sequence'].max()

# half point for each year
half_point = total_races // 2

# aligning the indexes of dnf_counts and half_point
dnf_counts.set_index(['year', 'sequence'], inplace=True)
half_point = half_point.reindex(dnf_counts.index, level='year')

# Split into the first half and second half of the season
first_half_dnf = dnf_counts[dnf_counts.index.get_level_values('sequence') <= half_point].groupby('year')['dnf_count'].sum()
second_half_dnf = dnf_counts[dnf_counts.index.get_level_values('sequence') > half_point].groupby('year')['dnf_count'].sum()

# line graph with two separate lines for first half and second half
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(first_half_dnf.index, first_half_dnf.values, label='First Half')
plt.plot(second_half_dnf.index, second_half_dnf.values, label='Second Half')

plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Number of DNFs')
plt.title('Number of DNFs in First Half vs. Second Half of the Season')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

years = total_races.index.unique()

new_index = pd.Index(years, name='year')

x = np.arange(len(years))

3.3 Conclusion:¶

The graph above shows that there isn't a big difference in a DNFs when the race sequence is taken into account. For the big jump in 2005 I assume that there was some change in recording the DNFs.
